UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '步道入口牌坊',
  name_en = 'Trail Entrance Archway',
  body = '<p>The Trail Entrance Archway stands at the main entrance of Shancheng Trail on Zhongxing Road in Yuzhong District, a stone archway combining traditional Ba-Yu architectural style with modern urban wayfinding. It features a four-pillar, three-bay structure in blue-gray stone, with gilded characters "山城步道" (Shancheng Trail) engraved on the crossbeam and couplets depicting old Chongqing street life carved on the flanking pillars—solemn, classical, and highly recognizable. Behind the archway begins the trail''s core uphill section, where stone steps wind upward along the mountainside, with old residences and new viewing platforms alternating on both sides. The moment you pass beneath the archway, you officially enter the time corridor of Shancheng Trail. A small plaza in front of the archway features a trail map and historical introduction panels, making it the first stop for visitors to understand the full route and plan their walk. The archway itself is a popular photo spot—especially at dusk when warm lights illuminate the carved characters against the layered silhouette of mountain-city buildings behind.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_mountain_trails_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '厚庐',
  name_en = 'Houlu Residence',
  body = '<p>Houlu Residence is a historically significant Republic-era building along the middle section of Shancheng Trail, originally built in the 1930s–40s during the War of Resistance as a private mansion of a military-political official. The two-story brick-and-wood structure faces north and is built against the hillside, with a blue-brick facade, traditional gray-tile roof, clean eave lines, and a portico supported by square pillars—reflecting the East-meets-West architectural style of the Republic era, combining the solid simplicity of traditional Ba-Yu dwellings with the geometric order of Western architecture. The name "Houlu" derives from the Chinese saying "thick virtue carries all things," and the stone plaque above the doorway remains well-preserved. The interior retains original wooden staircases, latticed windows, and period furnishings, offering a time-travel experience back to the wartime era. Several other contemporary buildings surround Houlu, forming a relatively complete Republic-era architectural cluster. As a key node in Shancheng Trail''s historical fabric, Houlu is not just a building but a microcosm of Chongqing''s memory as the wartime capital.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_mountain_trails_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '悬空栈道',
  name_en = 'Suspended Cliffside Walkway',
  body = '<p>The Suspended Cliffside Walkway is the most visually striking and experiential section of Shancheng Trail, built cantilevered off the cliff face in Yuzhong District. It extends over 100 meters with a width of 1.5 to 2 meters, with sections paved in transparent glass, revealing the vertical cliff drop of tens of meters below and the layered rooftops of the old town—an experience of pure visual thrill. The walkway uses steel beams as its skeleton, with anti-corrosion wood and tempered glass as surface materials, and stainless steel railings with wire mesh that minimize visual obstruction while ensuring safety. Walking along, one side is the solid mountain rock face, the other an abruptly open panorama—distant views of the Yangtze River and the South Bank skyline, close-up views of the dense gray-tiled rooftops and crisscrossing stone alleys of Shancheng Lane''s old quarter. On clear days, sunlight refracts through the glass panels in dappled patterns, creating a fascinating contrast with the old-town atmosphere below. At dusk, it is a prime spot to watch sunset glow illuminate the Yangtze, as warm orange light intertwines with the mountain-city skyline, forming a three-dimensional landscape painting unique to Chongqing.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_mountain_trails_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '仁爱荒野剧场',
  name_en = 'Ren''ai Wilderness Theater',
  body = '<p>Ren''ai Wilderness Theater is located on the upper section of Shancheng Trail, on the site of the former Ren''ai Church. After a thoughtful redesign, it has become an open-air theater blending historical ruins with wild aesthetic sensibility. The preserved remnants of the old church serve as a backdrop—stone walls covered in vines and moss, where the mottled marks of time contrast with and complement new plant growth. The center features a semicircular terraced stone seating area accommodating about 100 people, with a simple stage built from reclaimed wood and stone. The overall design is rugged and unadorned yet reveals carefully curated artistic intention at every turn. Native wildflowers and ornamental grasses surround the theater—lush and fragrant in spring and summer, evoking a melancholy poetry of bare branches in autumn and winter. Small concerts, poetry readings, theatrical performances, and outdoor screenings are held here regularly, and the space often becomes a spontaneous gathering spot for street artists and creative souls. Even on days without performances, simply sitting in this ruin-garden listening to wind and birdsong while gazing at the mountain-city skyline is enough to feel the unique cultural warmth and romantic undertone of Chongqing.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_mountain_trails_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '轨道李子坝站1号出口',
  name_en = 'Metro Liziba Station Exit 1',
  body = '<p>Metro Liziba Station Exit 1 is located on the side of the station building facing the Jialing River, serving as the primary entrance for visitors to experience the train-through-building marvel up close. Following the signs from inside the station to Exit 1, the moment you push open the glass doors and look up, you can see Line 2 trains gliding through the residential building overhead, just an arm''s length away. The engine sound and laundry hanging from residents'' windows create a fascinating coexistence. Simple guideboards and marked photo spots outside the exit indicate the best shooting angles and approximate train schedules. Many visitors linger here waiting for the perfect moment a train passes through, pressing the shutter to capture this urban wonder. The exit connects directly to Liziba Zheng Street, with steps leading down to the observation platform, making it the natural starting point for exploring the entire attraction.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_liziba_monorail_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '李子坝观景平台',
  name_en = 'Liziba Observation Platform',
  body = '<p>The Liziba Observation Platform is located on the Binjiang Road side of the Jialing River opposite Liziba Station. It was specially built by the Yuzhong District government in 2017 to provide a safe, spacious shooting space for the growing number of visitors. Covering approximately 1,500 square meters, the platform features a cantilevered steel structure extending several meters toward the Jialing River, offering an extremely open view. Looking up from here, the scene of Line 2 trains passing through the 6th to 8th floors of the residential building is fully visible—the best position for the classic train-through-building shot. Colorful graffiti and marked photo spots on the platform floor indicate recommended distances for shooting. The platform is equipped with sunshades, seating, drinking water facilities, and an electronic display showing real-time train arrival information. During holidays, the platform is packed with visitors and cameras, making it one of Chongqing''s most popular internet-famous spots.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_liziba_monorail_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '岩之魂浮雕文化墙',
  name_en = 'Spirit of Rock Relief Culture Wall',
  body = '<p>The Spirit of Rock Relief Culture Wall is located on the hillside retaining slope next to the Liziba Observation Platform—a large relief art group created on the existing retaining wall surface. The relief spans over 100 meters in length and several meters in height, with Chongqing''s unique landscape and cultural history as its creative thread. Classic Ba-Yu imagery—stilt houses, stone-paved roads, riverside piers, boat trackers, and old city gates—are layered and carved into the rock face. From afar it resembles an unfolded giant scroll; up close, rich details emerge: an old man carrying water, children at play, fishing boats rowing on the river—each scene vividly recreating old Chongqing''s street life. The relief combines realistic and impressionistic techniques, with bold, powerful lines and distinct light-and-shadow layers that produce different visual effects under varying sunlight. The wall not only beautifies the otherwise plain slope but also adds a cultural immersion experience for visitors waiting for trains, making it an unmissable artistic highlight of the Liziba area.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_liziba_monorail_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '文旅服务中心',
  name_en = 'Cultural Tourism Service Center',
  body = '<p>D拼装模型等特色商品。多媒体体验区则通过大屏播放李子坝轻轨建设历程纪录片和360度全景影像，让游客了解这一工程奇迹背后的故事。中心还提供行李寄存和无障碍通道服务，是游览李子坝的第一站和最佳补给点。 The Cultural Tourism Service Center is located near the Liziba Observation Platform, serving as the core supporting facility for the entire Liziba train-through-building attraction. The center features a modern, clean glass-curtain-wall exterior that creates an interesting contrast with the surrounding old mountain-city streets. Inside, it has four functional zones: a visitor information desk, rest area, cultural merchandise display area, and multimedia experience area. The information desk is staffed with bilingual (Chinese-English) personnel providing attraction maps, train schedules, and nearby dining recommendations. The rest area offers comfortable seating and free drinking water for visitors waiting between train pass-throughs. The merchandise area sells train-through-building-themed souvenirs including fridge magnets, postcards, hand-drawn maps, and 3D assembly models. The multimedia area plays documentaries about the construction of Liziba Metro and 360-degree panoramic footage on large screens, letting visitors understand the story behind this engineering marvel. The center also provides luggage storage and barrier-free access, making it the ideal first stop and supply point.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_liziba_monorail_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '巴渝旧闻馆',
  name_en = 'Ba-Yu Old News Gallery',
  body = '<p>The Ba-Yu Old News Gallery is a distinctive cultural venue within the Liziba train-through-building attraction, themed around modern Chongqing newspapers and journalism. Through physical exhibits, illustrated panels, and multimedia interactives, it presents a century of evolution in Chongqing''s press and public opinion—from the late Qing and early Republic to the reform and opening-up era. The gallery houses a collection of original and reprinted old newspapers, including historically significant titles such as Chongqing Daily, Xin Shu Bao, and Ta Kung Pao, whose front pages record major historical moments of Chongqing as wartime capital, industrial hub, and municipality. An "Old Papers, New Read" interactive station lets visitors browse electronic versions of vintage newspapers via touchscreen, experiencing the reading feel of the lead-type era. Themed wall panels connect key nodes in Chongqing''s press history—from the story of Baixiang Street''s "Newspaper Row" to the wartime years of Xinhua Daily in Chongqing. This micro-gallery hidden beside the train-through-building offers visitors a unique window into understanding Chongqing through the lens of journalism.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_liziba_monorail_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '轨道穿楼主体建筑',
  name_en = 'Train-Through-Building Main Structure',
  body = '<p>The train-through-building main structure is a multi-use residential-commercial building on Liziba Zheng Street in Yuzhong District, built in the early 2000s, and also the station building for Liziba Station on Chongqing Metro Line 2. The 19-story building houses the metro platform and tracks on the 6th to 8th floors, with trains passing directly through the middle of the structure. The lower floors (1–5) contain shops, and the upper floors (9–19) house residential apartments. This unique "rail-residential coexistence" design is extremely rare both nationally and globally. Its secret lies in the independent load-bearing structure and vibration isolation system between the track level and residential floors—track beams are supported by dedicated columns completely separated from the residential floor slabs, so residents upstairs barely feel vibration or noise when trains pass through. The exterior is clad in light-colored tiles, with two square openings where trains emerge and re-enter serving as the most recognizable visual symbols. Each time a train roars through, the massive body emerging from and disappearing into the building is a textbook example of urban architecture and rail transit integration, making this building one of Chongqing''s most famous city cards.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_liziba_monorail_sa_06';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '朝天门广场与两江交汇',
  name_en = 'Chaotianmen Square and the Confluence of Two Rivers',
  body = '<p>nightly两江游船由此启航。来福士广场建筑群矗立于广场后方，如风帆拔地而起，与朝天门的历史厚重形成新旧对话。夜幕降临，两岸灯光璀璨倒映江面，是拍摄重庆夜景的绝佳机位。 Chaotianmen Square sits at the confluence of the Yangtze and Jialing rivers, and has been Chongqing''s water gateway and urban origin since ancient times. Standing at the front railing, visitors can see the jade-green Jialing River on the left and the muddy-yellow Yangtze on the right, forming a striking two-color waterline where the rivers meet. Chaotianmen was first built in the early Ming Dynasty and was the largest of the seventeen ancient city gates. Today, after multiple renovations, the square has become a core landmark for leisure and sightseeing. Below lies Chaotianmen Pier, where nightly river cruise boats depart. The Raffles City complex rises behind the square like a cluster of sails, creating a dialogue between old and new. At night, dazzling lights from both banks reflect on the water, making it one of the best spots to photograph Chongqing''s nightscape.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_raffles_city_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '购物中心中庭与山城花园',
  name_en = 'Shopping Mall Atrium and Mountain City Garden',
  body = '<p>The Raffles City shopping mall atrium draws inspiration from Chongqing''s mountainous terrain, creating a tiered, three-dimensional space that mimics the traditional stilt-house architecture built along hillsides, cleverly blending commercial space with the city''s topography. The atrium rises dozens of meters with skylights flooding natural light, and cascading greenery hangs from above to create an immersive rainforest-like atmosphere. The Mountain City Garden, located on the mall''s rooftop, is an open-air sky garden featuring over a hundred plant species native to Chongqing or adapted to subtropical climates. Winding paths connect multiple resting spots and viewing nodes overlooking the Jialing River and Chaotianmen Square—a peaceful urban oasis. The mall hosts international and local designer brands, and the atrium regularly features art exhibitions and seasonal installations, elevating the shopping experience into a cultural journey.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_raffles_city_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '水晶连廊（探索舱·观景台）',
  name_en = 'The Crystal (Exploration Deck · Observation Deck)',
  body = '<p>AR体验装置。日落时分，金色阳光洒满江面，是拍摄两江交汇与朝天门全景的最佳时机。 The Crystal is the most iconic architectural element of Raffles City—a approximately 300-meter-long crystal bridge spanning the tops of four 250-meter-tall towers, suspended like a crystal arc above the mountain city''s skyline. Designed by internationally acclaimed architect Moshe Safdie, it draws inspiration from the "sail" imagery of Chongqing''s millennia-old shipping culture. The Exploration Deck, located inside the Crystal, is the public observation experience area. Through floor-to-ceiling panoramic glass walls, visitors can enjoy 360-degree views of the Yangtze and Jialing rivers'' confluence, the rolling peaks of Nanshan in the distance, and Yuzhong Peninsula''s urban forest below. Interactive exhibits introduce Chongqing''s river geography and urban evolution, with high-definition telescopes and AR devices. At sunset, golden light floods the river—the best time to photograph the two-river confluence and Chaotianmen panorama.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_raffles_city_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '探索舱·云端乐园',
  name_en = 'Exploration Deck · Sky Wonderland',
  body = '<p>VR技术模拟乘船穿越两江峡谷的震撼体验；星空漫步区在天花板安装LED星空穹顶，营造漫步云端银河的梦幻氛围。最受欢迎的当属高空玻璃观景栈道，透明玻璃地板悬空250米，脚下便是朝天门广场与两江汇流，胆大的游客可体验凌空行走的极致刺激。乐园还设有主题文创商店和云端咖啡吧，供游客在高空享受悠闲下午茶。整个体验约需1.5至2小时，是来福士最热门的深度体验项目。 The Exploration Deck · Sky Wonderland is an upgraded immersive experience within the Crystal, combining technology interaction, art installations, and themed adventure on top of basic observation. The wonderland features multiple themed zones: the City Memory Zone uses holographic projections and touchscreens to showcase Chongqing''s millennia of evolution from ancient pier to modern metropolis; the River Exploration Zone uses VR to simulate the thrilling experience of boating through two-river gorges; the Star Walk Zone features an LED starry sky ceiling creating a dreamy atmosphere of walking among clouds and galaxies. The most popular attraction is the high-altitude glass observation walkway—a transparent glass floor suspended 250 meters above Chaotianmen Square and the river confluence, offering the ultimate thrill of walking on air. A themed merchandise shop and cloud-top café let visitors enjoy afternoon tea at altitude. The full experience takes about 1.5 to 2 hours, making it Raffles City''s most popular in-depth attraction.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_raffles_city_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '天龙桥',
  name_en = 'Tianlong Bridge (Heavenly Dragon Bridge)',
  body = '<p>Tianlong Bridge is the first natural stone arch bridge in Wulong''s Three Natural Bridges scenic area and the most imposing of the three. The bridge was formed from limestone deposited on an ancient seabed hundreds of millions of years ago, subsequently uplifted by tectonic movement and sculpted by water erosion and collapse. The arch stands approximately 235 meters high, with a bridge deck about 150 meters thick, 147 meters wide, and a span of about 34 meters—like a colossal stone rainbow spanning two cliff faces. The irregularly shaped arch opening allows sunlight to pour through from above, casting dappled light and shadow across the valley floor in a magnificent, dreamlike display. A winding stone-paved trail passes beneath the bridge, with ferns and vines clinging to the rock walls and moss-covered rubble scattered about, as if entering an ancient secret realm. The most famous feature is an eagle-shaped natural rock formation at the top of the arch and the "Thread Spring" trickling from beneath the vault. The hidden courier station from Zhang Yimou''s film "Curse of the Golden Flower" was filmed beneath Tianlong Bridge, and the replica structure remains as a must-visit photo spot. Walking beneath the bridge and looking up at the enormous vault overhead, one feels the overwhelming majesty of nature and the smallness of humanity.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '仙女山国家公园-大草原站',
  name_en = 'Fairy Mountain National Park – Da Caoyuan Station (Great Meadow Station)',
  body = '<p>Da Caoyuan Station is the core stop of the Fairy Mountain National Park sightseeing train, located about 4 km after Mutizi Station at an elevation of approximately 2,000 meters. The moment visitors step off the train, the view opens dramatically—a vast alpine meadow stretching to the horizon, covering more than ten square kilometers, often called the "Switzerland of the East." The grassland undulates gently like a green velvet carpet—emerald green with scattered wildflowers in spring and summer (most commonly purple verbena, yellow coreopsis, and white wild strawberry blossoms), with cattle, sheep, and horses grazing peacefully in a pastoral idyll. In autumn, the meadow turns golden brown, contrasting vividly with the dark green Cryptomeria forest in the distance; in winter, thick snow transforms it into a rare southern snowfield, where the park operates a ski area and snow activities. After disembarking, visitors can choose from multiple experiences: horseback riding is the most classic, with local herdsmen leading horses along set routes for a leisurely "vast sky, boundless plain" experience; kite flying is also extremely popular, as the highland winds keep colorful kites dancing overhead; archery, grass sliding, and off-road go-karting are also available. A rest area, snack shop, and yurt-themed restaurant beside the station provide supplies and respite. Da Caoyuan Station is where visitors spend the most time—with most staying at least 2–3 hours to enjoy the abundant activities.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '天官赐福',
  name_en = 'Tianguan Cifu (Heavenly Official''s Blessing)',
  body = '<p>Tianguan Cifu is a unique natural cliff-face feature beneath Tianlong Bridge in the Three Natural Bridges scenic area. On the inner wall of the northern arch of Tianlong Bridge, a pattern of stone veins—formed over hundreds of millions of years through water erosion and mineral staining—strikingly resembles the four Chinese characters "天官赐福" (Heavenly Official''s Blessing). The strokes appear vigorous and well-structured, as if an immortal had used a finger as a brush to write on the cliff face. This coincidence has circulated in folklore for generations; local people regard it as an auspicious mark bestowed by a heavenly official descending to earth. During New Year and major celebrations, nearby villagers come to burn incense and pray for favorable weather and household peace. The surrounding cliff also bears natural patterns resembling auspicious clouds, bats, and ruyi motifs, further reinforcing the auspicious symbolism of fortune, prosperity, longevity, and happiness. The scenic area has installed a viewing platform, information plaque, and soft lighting so visitors can appreciate this natural wonder under various conditions. Geologically, the pattern results from differential weathering of varying mineral compositions in the limestone and iron oxide staining—a natural formation that, due to its striking resemblance to Chinese characters, has become one of the most culturally significant geological wonders of the Wulong Karst.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '青龙桥',
  name_en = 'Qinglong Bridge (Azure Dragon Bridge)',
  body = '<p>Qinglong Bridge is the second natural stone arch bridge in the Three Natural Bridges scenic area and the tallest of the three, with an arch height of approximately 281 meters, a deck thickness of about 168 meters, a width of about 124 meters, and a span of about 31 meters—ranking among the tallest natural stone arch bridges in the world. The bridge spans a near-vertical karst canyon, resembling a colossal stone archway standing between heaven and earth. The name comes from a beautiful natural phenomenon: at sunrise, sunlight slants through the arch opening, and the light refracts through mist and water vapor to form a blue-green beam crossing the canyon—like an azure dragon soaring through the bridge. A stream flows along the valley floor, with stalactites hanging from the rock walls in various forms—some like swords piercing the ground, others like lotus buds about to bloom. The arch ceiling has developed alcoves and natural stone eaves through weathering. During the rainy season, water cascades from these eaves like a bead curtain, with rainbows appearing in the sunlight—a dreamlike scene. A viewing platform beneath Qinglong Bridge offers one of the best vantage points for photographing the "soaring azure dragon" sunrise spectacle and classic panoramic views of the Three Natural Bridges.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '神鹰天坑',
  name_en = 'Shenying Tiankeng (Divine Eagle Doline)',
  body = '<p>Shenying Tiankeng is a large karst collapse doline situated between Tianlong Bridge and Qinglong Bridge in the Three Natural Bridges scenic area. The doline has an elliptical plan with a rim diameter of about 200–300 meters and a depth of approximately 195 meters, with a total volume of several million cubic meters—a world-class karst collapse feature. The doline is enclosed by nearly vertical limestone cliffs whose surfaces, through differential weathering, have formed numerous lifelike rock formations. The most striking is a protruding boulder on the eastern rim that, from certain angles, resembles a soaring eagle with head held high, wings spread, and piercing gaze overlooking the doline floor—giving the feature its name "Divine Eagle." The doline floor is relatively flat, covered with thick collapse deposits and subsequently grown dense vegetation, forming a relatively isolated "hanging garden" ecosystem. Wildflowers carpet sunlit areas while ferns thrive in shady corners, and birds occasionally circle above. Visitors descend along a cliff-hugging boardwalk, appreciating the doline''s grandeur and the Eagle Rock from different heights and angles. Standing at the bottom looking up, the surrounding walls form a natural shaft with the sky cut into an irregular ellipse where clouds drift overhead—an extraordinary sense of isolation from the world.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_06';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '黑龙桥',
  name_en = 'Heilong Bridge (Black Dragon Bridge)',
  body = '<p>Heilong Bridge is the third and final natural stone arch bridge in the Three Natural Bridges scenic area, with an arch height of approximately 223 meters, a deck thickness of about 137 meters, a width of about 193 meters, and a span of about 28 meters. Unlike Tianlong Bridge''s grandeur and Qinglong Bridge''s height, Heilong Bridge is renowned for its depth, darkness, and unpredictability. The long, curving arch opening admits little sunlight, leaving the interior perpetually dim with cool breezes and the sound of flowing water—walking through feels like traversing a black dragon''s belly, hence the name "Black Dragon." The most famous feature is the natural perforation in the arch ceiling through which sunlight enters, creating a bright spot on the dark wall that slowly moves over time like a searchlight scanning the cave—dubbed the "Shadow Clock." Multiple remarkable micro-karst formations exist beneath: a stalactite platform resembling Guanyin seated on a lotus, rock strata sections as clean-cut as by knife, and miniature stalagmite clusters formed by perennial dripping. Near the exit, a narrow passage called "Dragon Gate" has walls nearly touching, admitting only one person sideways—after squeezing through, the space suddenly opens into a hidden paradise. Summer temperatures beneath Heilong Bridge are only about 18°C, making it a natural cooling refuge and the most adventure-filled of the three bridges.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_07';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '龙泉洞',
  name_en = 'Longquan Cave (Dragon Spring Cave)',
  body = '<p>Longquan Cave is hidden within a limestone cliff face near Heilong Bridge in the Three Natural Bridges scenic area—one of the most mysterious cave features in the park. The entrance is concealed beneath a moss-covered cliff, where a clear mountain spring gushes from within, cascading along the rock face into a thin stream that drops to the valley floor. The perpetual flow and the low, dragon-like rumble of the water give it the name "Dragon Spring." The explored length extends several hundred meters, divided into front and rear chambers. The front chamber is spacious with a vault about 15 meters high, walls covered in diverse stalactites and stone curtains—some like inverted lotus flowers, others like terraced fields or hanging silk drapes—gleaming under lighting. The rear chamber is deeper and narrower, requiring visitors to stoop; the ceiling is dense with soda straw stalactites like a volley of arrows, while several stalagmites and columns rise from the floor. The tallest stalagmite, about 3 meters high, resembles a miniature pagoda, formed over tens of thousands of years of drip deposition. The cave maintains a constant temperature of about 16°C year-round—refreshingly cool in summer and misty in winter. Ancient marine fossils are visible on the cave walls, silently recounting the epic geological journey from ocean floor to mountain peak over hundreds of millions of years. Though smaller than Wulong''s Furong Cave, Longquan Cave''s exquisite delicacy and seamless integration with the Three Natural Bridges make it an unmissable hidden gem.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_08';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '龙水峡地缝',
  name_en = 'Longshuixia Difeng (Dragon Water Gorge Fissure)',
  body = '<p>Longshuixia Difeng is an important component of the Wulong Karst World Natural Heritage. It belongs to the same geological system as the Three Natural Bridges but presents a dramatically different landscape. The fissure extends about 5 km total with a developed tourist section of about 2 km—a deep gorge-type karst landform formed by the collapse of an underground river''s ceiling. At its narrowest, the gorge is only 1–2 meters wide, with near-vertical cliff walls 200–300 meters high. From the valley floor, the sky appears as a single thread—hence the names "Earth Fissure" and "Thread of Sky." A crystal-clear stream runs the length of the valley floor, jade-green in color, with water-polished boulders scattered throughout. Cliff-hugging boardwalks and suspended bridges wind through the gorge—visitors stroll along the streambank one moment and climb to mid-cliff aerial walkways the next, with only a sliver of sky overhead and rushing water below. Stalactites hang from the walls, thick with moss and ferns, as if entering a green tunnel toward the earth''s core. The microclimate is cool and humid, with air fragrant with plants and water mist; summer temperatures are about 10°C lower than outside. Multiple small waterfalls cascade from cliff crevices along the way, with mist and occasional rainbows. The most spectacular, Yinhe Waterfall, drops dozens of meters—the iconic feature of the fissure.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_09';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '银河飞瀑',
  name_en = 'Yinhe Waterfall (Milky Way Cascade)',
  body = '<p>Yinhe Waterfall is the largest and most awe-inspiring waterfall in the Longshuixia Difeng scenic area. Located at the mid-section of the gorge fissure, an abundant underground river source gushes from a natural crevice high on the cliff face, cascading down a near-vertical rock wall with a drop of several dozen meters. At full flow, the curtain spans 3–5 meters wide, roaring like thunder with mist filling the narrow gorge—an overwhelming spectacle. The great height and force shatter the water into countless fine droplets that refract sunlight into brilliant sparkles, like the Milky Way descending from heaven—hence the name "Milky Way Cascade." At its base, the waterfall collects into a deep emerald pool, clear to the bottom yet unfathomably deep, surrounded by mirror-smooth boulders polished by the current. From the viewing platform at the pool''s edge, mist washes over visitors—refreshingly cool in summer, while in winter it freezes into icicles and frost flowers adorning the cliffs, offering distinct beauty in every season. A natural alcove in the cliff behind the waterfall allows adventurous visitors to circle via a side boardwalk into the cave and look outward through the cascading curtain—a magical "Water Curtain Cave" experience. Yinhe Waterfall is the climactic section of the Longshuixia Difeng tour and one of the most memorable water features in the entire Wulong Karst tourist area.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_10';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '蛟龙寒窟',
  name_en = 'Jiaolong Hangu (Flood Dragon Cold Cave)',
  body = '<p>Jiaolong Hangu is located beneath a cliff deep within the Longshuixia Difeng scenic area—a natural large stone cavern formed by the combined action of karst dissolution and rock layer collapse. The entrance is low and concealed, half-hidden by dense ferns and moss, requiring visitors to duck to enter. The interior space covers several dozen square meters with a vault about 3–5 meters high. The walls are covered with grooves and dissolution pits formed by perennial water erosion, their surfaces wet and smooth, gleaming with a cold sheen under lighting. The cavern''s most notable feature is its exceptionally low temperature—about 12–14°C year-round. Even in midsummer, the chill upon entering is biting and bone-penetrating, with a temperature difference of more than 15°C from outside. A shallow cold pool occupies the cavern floor, crystal-clear and icy, inhabited by tiny blind fish and transparent shrimp—cave-dwelling species evolved for perpetual darkness, their bodies pale or colorless. Behind the pool, a narrow underground river channel extends deeper into the earth, its water echoing faintly, with even searchlights unable to reach the end—shrouding the cavern in mystery. Local folklore holds that a flood dragon once lurked here, its dragon breath becoming the perpetual cold mist, hence the name "Flood Dragon Cold Cave." Though modest in size, the extreme chill and mysterious underground ecosystem make this one of the most memorable exploration stops in the Longshuixia Difeng tour.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_11';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '仙女山国家公园-木梯子站',
  name_en = 'Fairy Mountain National Park – Mutizi Station',
  body = '<p>Mutizi Station is the starting station of the sightseeing train within Fairy Mountain National Park, located near the main park road entrance at an elevation of about 1,900 meters—the first stop for visitors entering the core scenic area. The name "Mutizi" (Wooden Ladder) originates from local history: a steep mountain path once paved with wooden stairs here was the main route for early mountain dwellers to gather herbs and graze livestock. After the road was built, the stairs fell into disuse, but the name endured. The station building features wooden construction with grey tiles in Ba-Yu mountain vernacular style, harmonizing with the surrounding pine forest and alpine meadows. The plaza in front includes a large visitor distribution area, ticket windows, a resting corridor, and park maps. After purchasing tickets, visitors board a vintage sightseeing train that runs along a circular railway through the park. The 12-kilometer route passes through dense Cryptomeria and cypress forests and alpine meadows with seasonal variation: lush green grass and wildflowers in spring and summer, layered autumn colors, and a silvery snowscape in winter resembling northern landscapes. Mutizi Station also houses a transfer center and ecological parking lot where self-driving visitors park before taking the train into the core scenic area. An open lawn beside the station is equipped with telescopes for viewing Fairy Mountain''s main peak and the rolling Wuling range—an ideal spot for warm-up photos before departure.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_wulong_karst_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '层空中公共连廊',
  name_en = 'th-Floor Sky Corridor',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Built in 1996, this 24-floor residential block has no elevator. The 10th-floor corridor links the three towers of the complex, offering unobstructed views of the Yangtze, the cable car, the Raffles City skyline and the Yangtze River Bridge—an iconic filming and viral-photography location famous for Chongqing''s "8D magic."</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_baixiangju_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '层解放东路出口（终点）',
  name_en = 'th-Floor Jiefang East Road Exit (Ending Point)',
  body = '<p>Long Description: This 15th-floor exit connects Baixiangju to Jiefang East Road and the Luohan Temple area via a 30-step descent. The platform offers a striking 3D-traffic view of Jiefang East Road, Minzu Road, Cangbai Road, the cable car and double-decker buses, marking the official end of the Baixiangju vertical tour.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_baixiangju_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '层临江入口（起点）',
  name_en = 'Ground-Floor Riverside Entrance (Starting Point)',
  body = '<p>Long Description: The riverside entrance on the ground floor of Baixiangju is the starting point of the vertical tour. It features two 2-meter stone elephants, a 1990s residential block hugging the Yangtze and the famous air-raid-shelter-turned-café that has become a viral photo spot for the Chongqing skyline and cable car.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_baixiangju_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '长江索道同框观景窗',
  name_en = 'Cable-Car Frame Window',
  body = '<p>Long Description: This framed cable-car shot, captured from the 10th-floor corridor''s east end with a 2–3x telephoto lens, places the Yangtze Cable Car and Baixiangju''s 24-story walk-up in the same frame. The result—an "8D" composition of building, cable car and river—has become a must-shoot for photographers worldwide.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_baixiangju_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '磁器长歌体验馆',
  name_en = '"Ciqi Changge" Immersive Experience Hall',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Opened in May 2023, Ciqi Changge is Ciqikou''s first large-scale immersive night-experience hall. Across five acts—Ancient Wharf, Old Street, Porcelain Kiln, Guild Hall, Wartime Capital—it uses AR, holograms, live performance and interactive lighting to compress 1,000 years of local history into a 60-minute walking show.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '黄桷坪牌坊',
  name_en = 'Huangjueping Memorial Arch',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Rebuilt in 2010 in classic Ming style, this 12-meter stone archway is the official entrance to Ciqikou Ancient Town. Flanked by two 100-year-old banyan trees and the "Ciqikou" name tablet, it marks the starting point of both the main street and the riverside tour routes.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '钟家院',
  name_en = 'Zhong Family Mansion',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Built in the Xianfeng era (1851–1861), the 1,500 m² Zhong Mansion is a three-bay Qing residence with a front shop and a back living area. Converted into the Bayu Folk-House Museum in 1998, it displays wedding customs, carved beds, ancestral tablets and other late-imperial artifacts of Bayu culture.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '宝善宫',
  name_en = 'Baoshan Palace',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Built in 1886 as a Jiangxi merchant guild hall, Baoshan Palace is the best-preserved of Ciqikou''s "Nine Palaces and Eighteen Temples." Refurbished in 2010, its teahouse hosts Sichuan opera seating performances daily, with bamboo chairs and 5-CNY covered-bowl tea—a perfect taste of old Chongqing.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '鑫记杂货铺',
  name_en = 'Xin''s Grocery',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Founded in 1894, Xin''s is a fourth-generation grocery and the only shop still using the traditional "front-shop-back-workshop" layout on Ciqikou''s main street. It sells malt sugar, sesame candy, hand-made soy sauce, Sichuan pepper broad-bean paste and dozens of other old Chongqing snacks—a living window into late-imperial market culture.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '聚森茂酱园旧址',
  name_en = 'Jusenmao Sauce Garden Site',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Founded in 1911, Jusenmao was once the largest sauce maker in Ciqikou, producing 500,000 jin of soy sauce, vinegar, bean paste and pickles a year. Partially demolished in 2003, its front shop and sun-curing yard were rebuilt in 2010 as a museum of traditional sauce culture, with 60+ vats on display.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_06';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '磁横街',
  name_en = 'Ciheng Street',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Built along the Jialing River cliff, the 200-meter "half-side street" is Ciqikou''s most authentic riverside market. With stilted houses, stone steps, dock-worker statues and ancient banyans, it preserves the late-Qing water-and-land transport hub that made Ciqikou a leading commercial port in eastern Sichuan.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_07';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '宝轮寺',
  name_en = 'Baolun Temple',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Founded in 1008 during the Tang dynasty, Baolun Temple is the origin of the "White Rock" name for Ciqikou. Rebuilt in the Kangxi era and bestowed the imperial name "Baolun Chan Temple" by Emperor Qianlong, it preserves a Kangxi plaque, Song stone Buddhas and Ming gilt-bronze statues—the three treasures of the temple.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_08';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '迎龙门码头',
  name_en = 'Yinglongmen Wharf',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Dating back to the Ming dynasty, Yinglongmen Wharf was one of the four major Jialing River ports in the late-Qing era, handling 300,000 tons of cargo annually. Restored in 2010 with its stone steps, mooring stones and river pavilion, it now hosts folk performers and is the boarding point for Jialing River cruise boats.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_09';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '九石缸河滩',
  name_en = 'Nine-Stone-Cap Riverside',
  body = '<p>Long Description: The viral "Little Kenting" beach, named after nine Qing-era stone vats once used to store drinking water for porcelain-export boats. Six of the nine vats survive today, lining a sandy Jialing River bank popular from May to October for wading, sunset views and winter misty mornings.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_ciqikou_old_town_sa_10';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '观音桥步行街广场',
  name_en = 'Guanyinqiao Pedestrian Street Plaza',
  body = '<p>Covering 58,000 sqm, the plaza was created during the 2003 redevelopment and now welcomes 150 million visitors a year. It links 10+ shopping malls, two metro lines and the central "Jinjie" underground street.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_guanyinqiao_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '茂业天地"裸眼 3D"大屏',
  name_en = 'Maoye Tiandi Naked-Eye 3D Screen',
  body = '<p>A 700 sqm curved P3 LED screen on Maoye Tiandi''s façade, lit in January 2021, displaying "Cyber Chongqing" 3D animations. It is one of the most photographed night attractions in the CBD.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_guanyinqiao_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '观音桥雕塑（城市标志）',
  name_en = 'Guanyinqiao Sculpture (City Landmark)',
  body = '<p>The 16.8 m stainless-steel sculpture with its "Guanyin praying" figure and Chongqing landscape base was unveiled in 2003, refurbished in 2018 and has become the central photo landmark of the CBD.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_guanyinqiao_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '北城天街',
  name_en = 'Beicheng Tianjie (North City Mall)',
  body = '<p>A 380,000 sqm shopping complex opened by Longfor in 2003, comprising Blocks A, B, C (Starlight 68) and X. It houses luxury brands, fashion, dining and entertainment, and is the CBD''s flagship mall.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_guanyinqiao_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '观音桥九街（不夜九街 - 终点）',
  name_en = 'Guanyinqiao Jiugie (Sleepless Jiugie - Terminal)',
  body = '<p>A 1.2 km nightlife zone with 200+ bars, live houses and 24 h eateries, opened as a pilot "night-economy district" in 2017. Open from 20:00 to 04:00, it is the after-dark terminal of the route.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_guanyinqiao_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '解放碑广场',
  name_en = 'Jiefangbei Square',
  body = '<p>Jiefangbei Square is located at the core of the pedestrian commercial district in Yuzhong District, centered on the People''s Liberation Monument and radiating outward in a circle roughly 200 meters in diameter. It is both the spiritual symbol and commercial heart of Chongqing. The site originated in 1940 as the "Spirit Fortress" commemorating the War of Resistance; the Anti-Japanese War Victory Monument was built here in 1946 and renamed "People''s Liberation Monument" by Liu Bocheng in 1950. Surrounded by WFC, Metropolitan Plaza and Pacific Department Store, the square draws over 300,000 visitors daily — the foremost commercial district in western China.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiefangbei_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '解放碑纪念碑',
  name_en = 'People''s Liberation Monument',
  body = '<p>The People''s Liberation Monument, standing 27.5 meters tall at the intersection of Minzu, Minquan and Zourong Roads, is an octagonal reinforced-concrete tower clad in reddish-brown granite, topped with a clock, wind vane and alarm bell. Originally named the "Anti-Japanese War Victory Monument" and laid in October 1946, it was renamed by Liu Bocheng in 1950. Designated a national-level protected cultural heritage site in 2013, it is the only monument in China commemorating the victory of both the Anti-Japanese War and the World Anti-Fascist War.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiefangbei_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '解放碑步行街雕塑群',
  name_en = 'Jiefangbei Pedestrian Street Sculpture Group',
  body = '<p>Scattered along the pedestrian zones radiating from the monument along Zourong, Minzu and Minquan Roads, this group of over a dozen bronze and stone sculptures was created between 1997 and the 2010s. Highlights include the "Century Chongqing" relief wall (depicting the city from treaty-port era to wartime capital), the "Bang-Bang Army" group (portraying porters), the "Down-River Migrants" figures (wartime evacuees), and a hotpot scene sculpture. Designed jointly by the Chongqing Sculptors Association and the Sichuan Fine Arts Institute, they form a touchable, photogenic three-dimensional memory of the city.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiefangbei_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '邹容路步行街',
  name_en = 'Zourong Road Pedestrian Street',
  body = '<p>Stretching about 1.2 km from Xiaoshizi in the east to Minsheng Road in the west, Zourong Road Pedestrian Street is named after Zou Rong (1885–1905), the Qing-dynasty revolutionary who wrote "The Revolutionary Army." Pedestrianized in 1997 — Chongqing''s earliest — it is flanked by veteran department stores (Chongqing Department Store, New Century) and modern complexes (Metropolitan Plaza, Yingli International). With over 500,000 daily visitors and over one million on holidays, it boasts the highest commercial sales efficiency in western China.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiefangbei_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '八一路好吃街',
  name_en = 'Bayi Road Good Food Street',
  body = '<p>Located on Bayi Road adjacent to the Jiefangbei pedestrian zone and stretching about 500 meters, this is one of the oldest and best-known food streets in central Chongqing. Over 200 stalls and shops line both sides, offering dozens of authentic Bayu snacks — sour-spicy noodles, Chongqing small noodles, grilled pig brain, skewered chicken, iced jelly, and mountain-city glutinous-rice balls — alongside viral spots like Zhou Shixiong Hotpot and Hao You Lai noodles. Originating as a spontaneous 1990s night market and formalized in 2008, it draws over 100,000 visitors daily.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiefangbei_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '环球金融中心会仙楼观景台',
  name_en = 'WFC Huixianlou Observation Deck',
  body = '<p>WFC）73层，建筑总高339米，是重庆目前最高的观景平台之一。观景台面积约2000平方米，设360度全透明环形玻璃幕墙，可俯瞰渝中半岛、长江与嘉陵江交汇、洪崖洞、千厮门大桥、来福士广场及南岸区天际线全貌。观景台分日场与夜场两时段运营，夜场可观赏重庆"百万夜景"灯光秀。台内设有高空咖啡吧、文创纪念品店及"云端邮筒"互动装置，亦是重庆"赛博朋克"城市天际线的最佳拍摄点之一，被称为"西部之巅"。 Perched on the 73rd floor of the Chongqing World Financial Center (WFC) in the Jiefangbei district, the Huixianlou Observation Deck sits 339 meters above sea level — among the highest viewing platforms in Chongqing. Its roughly 2,000 m², 360-degree glass curtain wall offers sweeping views of the Yuzhong Peninsula, the Yangtze–Jialing confluence, Hongyadong, Qiansimen Bridge, Raffles City and the Nan''an skyline. Operating in daytime and night sessions, the deck features a sky café, a souvenir shop and a "cloud mailbox" — one of the best vantage points for Chongqing''s cyber-punk skyline, nicknamed "the Summit of the West."</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiefangbei_sa_06';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '大门广场（起点）',
  name_en = 'Main Entrance Plaza (Starting Point)',
  body = '<p>Long Description: The semi-circular entrance plaza greets visitors with a giant panda flower bed, a golden "Chongqing Zoo" sign, palm and ginkgo trees, and bronze animal statues. It also houses the visitor center, ticket office, souvenir shop and the official park map—making it the natural starting point for any visit.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_zoo_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '熊猫馆',
  name_en = 'Panda Hall',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Built in the 1960s and modernized in the 2010s, Panda Hall is a multi-zone complex with indoor halls, outdoor playgrounds, a maternity ward and a kindergarten. Home to 10+ giant pandas, it is one of the largest breeding bases in western China and a flagship for panda research, conservation and education.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_zoo_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '金鱼馆',
  name_en = 'Goldfish Hall',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Built in the 1990s and refurbished in 2018, Goldfish Hall is a southwest-China landmark for goldfish appreciation. With four themed zones and ~60 varieties (dragon-eye, fantail, oranda, ranchu, celestial-eye, pearl-scale and more), it is a favorite for family visits and a regular venue for the National Goldfish Competition.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_zoo_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '两栖爬行动物馆',
  name_en = 'Amphibian and Reptile Hall',
  body = '<p>Long Description: Opened in 2005, the Amphibian and Reptile Hall is the largest herpetarium in southwest China. With two floors and habitats mimicking rainforest, marsh, rocky desert and river valley, it houses 60+ species and 300+ individuals, plus a "night-creature" interactive zone popular with school groups.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_zoo_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '鸟类区',
  name_en = 'Bird Area',
  body = '<p>Long Description: The 15,000 m² Bird Area is the largest and most diverse in the zoo, comprising six themed zones and home to nearly 100 species. Highlights include red-crowned cranes, mandarin ducks, golden pheasants, peafowl, hornbills, macaws, flamingos and the rare Chinese crested tern, with seasonal wild birds joining the resident flocks in spring and autumn.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_zoo_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '大门',
  name_en = 'Main Gate (North Gate)',
  body = '<p>The Main Gate sits at the foot of Jinfo Mountain''s north slope near Tianxing Town and serves as the first stop for most visitors. The entrance complex combines a large parking lot, visitor center, ticket windows and self-service kiosks where combined tickets for admission, cableway and shuttle can be purchased. An eco-shuttle bus ride of about 20 minutes reaches the cableway lower station, passing lower-zone sights such as Bitan Valley. The visitor center offers panoramic maps, rain-poncho rental and luggage storage, and doubles as the registration point for winter ski equipment. Outside the gate, Tianxing Town provides dining, lodging and specialty shops—a common base for two-day "valley-to-summit" itineraries.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '碧潭幽谷',
  name_en = 'Bitan Valley (Green Pool Secluded Gorge)',
  body = '<p>Located at 700–1,000 m elevation on Jinfo Mountain''s north slope, Bitan Valley is the key lower-zone landscape along the route from the main gate to the cableway lower station. The roughly 3 km gorge winds up along a mountain stream between steep, densely forested cliffs that shelter rare species such as yew and dove tree. Over a dozen deep pools dot the valley—the largest, "Bitan" (Emerald Pool), is jade-green and translucent, traditionally said to be where ancient monks washed their alms bowls. Wooden boardwalks and stone paths pass waterfalls, cascades and moss-covered walls; summer temperatures run 5–8 °C cooler than the base, making this a classic hot-season hiking route. The full walk takes about 1.5–2 hours.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_08';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '索道下站',
  name_en = 'Cableway Lower Station (North Slope)',
  body = '<p>The lower station of Jinfo Mountain''s north-slope cableway sits at about 1,100 m above Bitan Valley and is the mountain''s most critical transit hub. The cableway spans roughly 1,100 m with an elevation gain of about 600 m; each cabin holds dozens of passengers and the ride takes about five minutes, offering aerial views of gorges and primeval forest. The lower station has a waiting hall, ticket windows and a rest area; queues at peak times can reach 30–60 minutes, so off-peak travel is advised. An outside viewing platform frames the main summit ridge and serves as a key photo spot for winter snow and autumn foliage. Exiting the upper station places you at Qianniuping Sky Street—the gateway to the summit zone. The cableway may suspend operations in high wind or thunderstorms.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_06';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '牵牛坪天街',
  name_en = 'Qianniuping Sky Street',
  body = '<p>Qianniuping Sky Street lies at the exit of the north-slope cableway upper station at about 2,000 m, named after the Qianniuping meadow. It is the hub of Jinfo Mountain''s summit zone, with restaurants, specialty shops, a convenience store, a café and viewing terraces offering local delicacies such as square-bamboo shoots, Jinshan cured meat and alpine potatoes. A large route map at the plaza helps visitors choose directions: east to Golden Turtle and Cloud Walkway, west to Medicine Pool Dam and Ancient Buddha Cave, north to Arrow Bamboo Forest and Azalea Prince. In winter the street becomes the ski-service center with equipment rental and access to the ski slope. Lodging here makes summit sunrise and stargazing possible.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_10';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '箭竹林海',
  name_en = 'Arrow Bamboo Forest Sea',
  body = '<p>The Arrow Bamboo Forest Sea covers over 10 km² at 1,900–2,100 m on Jinfo Mountain''s summit, dominated by West-China arrow bamboo (Fargesia) standing 2–4 m tall in dense, sun-dimming stands. As a core zone of the national nature reserve, it shelters rare species such as musk deer, golden pheasant and white-crowned fork-tail, and lies along the southern potential corridor of the giant panda''s historical range. Wooden boardwalks thread through the groves—rustling leaves and cool breezes in summer, golden-tipped bamboo contrasting with autumn colors. Arrow bamboo flowers once every 60–120 years, after which entire stands die off and naturally regenerate, a key research subject for the mountain''s ecologists. An eco-education signboard and rest pavilion mark the entrance.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_11';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '金龟朝阳',
  name_en = 'Golden Turtle Facing the Sun',
  body = '<p>Golden Turtle Facing the Sun perches on the eastern cliff edge of Qianniuping at about 2,100 m and is one of Jinfo Mountain''s most recognizable rock formations. Shaped from Cambrian limestone over hundreds of millions of years of weathering and dissolution, the roughly 10 m long, 5 m high boulder resembles—when viewed from the east—a giant stone turtle lifting its head toward the sun, its shell, head and limbs clearly defined. Facing open valleys to the east, it is the mountain''s premier sunrise spot: dawn clouds churn, the sun crests the ridge, and golden light floods the turtle''s back. A wooden viewing platform with safety rails and an interpretive sign stands here; connecting trails lead to the Cloud Walkway and cliff-hugging plank road, making it the key node of the summit''s eastern route.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_12';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '云端步道',
  name_en = 'Cloud Walkway',
  body = '<p>The Cloud Walkway runs along the cliff face between Qianniuping and Golden Turtle at 2,000–2,100 m, stretching about 1.5 km—the most iconic aerial route on Jinfo Mountain''s eastern summit. Carved along a karst escarpment with sections of cantilevered steel, it places a rock wall on one side and a plunging valley on the other; when mist swirls in, walking it feels like treading on clouds—hence the name. Three projecting viewing platforms offer views of the Nanchuan mountain ranges and the lower-zone gorges, and are prime spots for the mountain''s "Buddha''s halo" and sea of clouds. The full route has safety rails and anti-slip surfacing; it may close in rain, and those with acrophobia should proceed with caution. A safety signboard and rest pavilion mark the entrance.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_13';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '燕子洞和灵观洞',
  name_en = 'Swallow Cave and Lingguan Cave',
  body = '<p>Swallow Cave and Lingguan Cave lie about 200 m apart on the west side of Qianniuping and form key parts of Jinfo Mountain''s karst-cave system. Swallow Cave has a roughly 15 m wide, 8 m high entrance opening into a spacious chamber where thousands of rock swallows nest year-round; in spring and summer they dart in and out like dark arrows—hence the name. Inside, an underground stream and stalagmites, curtains and flowstone decorate the chamber. Lingguan Cave is named for a Daoist Lingguan statue once placed at its mouth; its interior features stalactites, columns and cave flowers, with some walls bearing natural "Buddha" silhouettes where monks and Daoist priests once practiced. Both caves are lit and equipped with boardwalks; the interior temperature holds at 12–15 °C, so an extra layer is advisable in summer. Visiting both takes about 40–60 minutes.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_14';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '杜鹃王子',
  name_en = 'Azalea Prince',
  body = '<p>Rhododendron rex），树高约12米，胸径约40厘米，冠幅近8米，是金佛山已发现的最大野生杜鹃古树，故被尊称为"杜鹃王子"。金佛山是中国杜鹃花科植物多样性中心之一，分布有弯尖杜鹃、金山杜鹃、树枫杜鹃等40余种杜鹃，其中特有种超过10种。每年4至5月花季，杜鹃王子满树繁花，花冠直径可达10厘米，粉红至深红色花朵层层叠叠，与周围箭竹、苔藓及远山彩林相映成画，是金佛山春季摄影与植物研学的核心打卡点。树旁设木栈道与观景台，并立有植物科普说明牌。 The "Azalea Prince" stands at the edge of the Arrow Bamboo Forest at about 2,050 m—an estimated 1,000-year-old wild Rhododendron rex, roughly 12 m tall, 40 cm in trunk diameter and nearly 8 m across the crown, making it the largest ancient wild rhododendron discovered on Jinfo Mountain. The mountain is a diversity center for Chinese rhododendrons, hosting over 40 species including more than 10 endemics. Each April–May the Prince bursts into bloom, its 10 cm-wide flowers ranging from pink to deep crimson, layered against a backdrop of bamboo, moss and multicolored forests—the most photographed spot of Jinfo Mountain''s spring season and a key site for botanical education. A boardwalk, viewing platform and interpretive sign stand beside the tree.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_15';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '药池坝',
  name_en = 'Yaochiba (Medicine Pool Dam)',
  body = '<p>Yaochiba sits southwest of Qianniuping at about 2,000 m—a roughly 30,000 m² alpine meadow and wetland complex. The flat, grassy expanse is dotted with dozens of natural mineral springs and pools; Jinfo Mountain monks once drew water here to brew herbal remedies, giving the place its name ("Medicine Pool"). Surrounded by arrow bamboo and rhododendron shrub, with the Jinfo summit ridge and karst pinnacles on the horizon, the meadow turns golden in autumn against layered forests—one of the mountain''s signature fall scenes. Boardwalks, rest pavilions and viewing platforms are provided, and the dam is a popular camping and stargazing spot. Westward trails lead to Ancient Buddha Cave and Jinfo Temple; southward to the Ecological Stone Forest.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '古佛洞',
  name_en = 'Gufo Cave (Ancient Buddha Cave)',
  body = '<p>Gufo Cave lies west of Yaochiba at about 2,000 m and is the largest explored karst cave on Jinfo Mountain, with a total passage length of about 3 km and a developed tour route of roughly 1.2 km. Natural stone Buddha carvings at the entrance—believed to have been chiseled by monks in the Ming–Qing era from existing rock formations—gave the cave its name ("Ancient Buddha"). The interior is vast: the largest chamber rises about 30 m high and exceeds 5,000 m² in area, filled with stalagmites, stalactites, columns, curtains and cave flowers. The "Sea-Calming Pillar," a 15 m-tall, 1 m-diameter column, is the cave''s signature feature. Warm-yellow lighting enhances the Buddhist atmosphere, with several stone Buddha figures and sutra inscriptions along the route. The cave holds at 11–14 °C year-round with high humidity—wear non-slip footwear. The full walk takes 50–70 minutes.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '金佛顶',
  name_en = 'Jinfo Summit (Jinfo Peak)',
  body = '<p>At about 2,238 m, Jinfo Summit is the highest point and spiritual symbol of Jinfo Mountain. The mountain takes its name from the main ridge''s resemblance to a reclining Buddha when seen from a distance, and the summit occupies the "head" position. From the top, visitors can survey 360° of the Dalou range; on clear days the Guizhou Dalou main ridge and Nanchuan city are visible. Nearby stands Jinfo Temple (Fengzui Temple), the mountain''s Buddhist heart—originally founded in the Song dynasty with later reconstructions, housing statues of Shakyamuni and Guanyin. The summit viewing platform with safety rails is the premier spot for sunrise, sea of clouds, "Buddha''s halo" and stargazing. In winter, snow can accumulate to tens of centimeters, creating a rare southern snow-field scene. The walk from Qianniuping Sky Street takes 40–50 minutes, partly on stone steps.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '生态石林',
  name_en = 'Ecological Stone Forest',
  body = '<p>Covering about 2 km² south of Yaochiba at roughly 2,000 m, the Ecological Stone Forest is a key element of Jinfo Mountain''s karst landscape. Unlike the bare stone teeth of Yunnan''s Shilin, Jinfo''s pinnacles and stone buds are cloaked in moss, ferns, shrubs and trees—stone and forest merged into one, earning the name "living stone forest." The pinnacles, 3–8 m tall, take myriad forms—swords pointing skyward, beasts crouching among trees—interspersed with arrow bamboo, rhododendron and rare square bamboo, creating a unique "forest-on-stone" micro-ecosystem. In 2014 Jinfo Mountain was inscribed as part of the "South China Karst" Phase II World Natural Heritage, with the Ecological Stone Forest as a core heritage element. Boardwalks and interpretive signs guide visitors through a 30–40 minute walk—the best outdoor classroom for the mountain''s karst geology and biodiversity.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '西门游客中心',
  name_en = 'West Gate Visitor Center',
  body = '<p>The West Gate Visitor Center stands at the foot of the west slope beside the West Gate Cableway Lower Station, serving as the main entrance and service hub for the western route. The building blends modern functionality with mountain vernacular style, housing a large ticketing hall, self-service kiosks, an information desk, luggage storage, rain-poncho rental and a first-aid point, where visitors can purchase admission, cableway and shuttle combo tickets. Outside are a large parking lot, restrooms, dining outlets and specialty shops selling square-bamboo shoots, Nanchuan rice and dried local produce. Inside, a geology-and-biodiversity exhibit uses panels and specimens to introduce Jinfo Mountain''s World Natural Heritage karst geology, rare flora and fauna and rhododendron resources—an ideal "knowledge stop" before heading uphill. The walk from the center to the cableway lower station is about 3 minutes.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jinfo_mountain_sa_07';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '北站（渝中区新华路站）',
  name_en = 'North Station (Xinhua Road Station, Yuzhong District)',
  body = '<p>The North Station of the Yangtze River Cableway is located near the intersection of Xinhua Road and Cangbai Road in the Xiaoshizi commercial area of Yuzhong District—the Yuzhong starting station and the preferred departure point for most visitors. The station building is a multi-story cableway complex with a light grey exterior and a prominent red "Yangtze River Cableway" sign that has become one of the iconic elements of the Yuzhong Peninsula skyline. The ground floor houses the ticket hall and waiting area with self-service machines and staffed windows. During peak season, queues can reach one to two hours—advance booking via the official mini-program is recommended. After purchasing tickets, visitors take an elevator to the high-level platform, a semi-open structure enclosed on three sides and open toward the river. A large floor-to-ceiling glass window lets waiting visitors overlook the dense urban fabric of the Yuzhong Peninsula and the rolling mountains of the south bank. The station''s greatest advantage is that departing cabins ascend from among the Yuzhong Peninsula''s high-rises, cross over the layered city roofline, and suddenly span the Yangtze—the visual transition from "city to river" is spectacular, making it the best starting point for panoramic photos of the peninsula and Yangtze skyline. A cableway history exhibition area beside the station displays archival construction photos and engineering documentation.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_yangtze_cableway_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '索道轿厢',
  name_en = 'Cableway Cabin',
  body = '<p>landmarks，夜晚乘坐更能欣赏渝中半岛灯火璀璨的夜景，是重庆最具代表性的城市体验项目之一。 The Yangtze River Cableway cabin is the core vehicle of the entire cableway experience, suspended on a carrying cable strung high above the Yangtze and hauled by a traction machine between North and South Stations. The cableway was completed and opened in 1987, with a total length of approximately 1,166 meters, a maximum height of about 60 meters above ground, and a one-way journey of about 4–5 minutes. The cabin features a bright yellow exterior, about 6.5 meters long, 1.5 meters wide, and 2 meters high, accommodating about 20–25 standing passengers. Large tempered glass windows on all four sides provide expansive views—the river surface, urban architecture on both banks, and rolling mountains are all clearly visible from front, sides, and below. The ride is unforgettable: the cabin departs slowly from the North Station platform, gradually accelerates, rises among dense city high-rises, and after crossing the north bank levee, the ground below suddenly becomes the open river—the mighty Yangtze flowing eastward, boats shuttling back and forth, with Chaotianmen Raffles City and Dongshuimen Bridge in the distance. At mid-river, the cabin sways gently with dozens of meters of rushing water below—thrilling and magnificent. On clear days, the Nanshan mountain peaks are visible in the distance; on foggy days, the cabin traverses through clouds like riding the mist. A voice guide inside introduces landmarks along the way. Night rides offer the dazzling illuminated skyline of the Yuzhong Peninsula—one of Chongqing''s most iconic urban experiences.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_yangtze_cableway_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '南站（南岸区龙门浩站）',
  name_en = 'South Station (Longmenhao Station, Nan''an District)',
  body = '<p>CBD 在眼前一字排开，是拍摄渝中半岛经典天际线的最佳位置之一，尤其日落和夜景时分景色最为壮丽。从南站出发乘坐索道向北站方向行驶时，轿厢从南岸高地向江面下降，视野从俯瞰全城逐渐过渡到平视江面和仰视渝中半岛楼群，与从北站出发的上升视角形成互补。南站出站后步行5分钟即可到达龙门浩老街，10分钟可达东水门大桥步道，是串联索道体验与南岸滨江游览的理想节点。 The South Station of the Yangtze River Cableway is located in the Longmenhao area of Nan''an District, on a riverside highland along the south bank of the Yangtze—the cableway''s southern terminal and the departure station for those boarding from the Nan''an side. Unlike the bustling Xiaoshizi commercial district where the North Station sits, the South Station''s surroundings are more leisurely and artistic—adjacent to the recently restored Longmenhao Old Street historic district, where blue-brick, dark-tile WWII-era buildings cascade up the hillside, dotted with cafés, teahouses, and creative boutiques. The station building is more compact than the North Station, with ticket windows, a waiting area, and a small observation platform. The platform level faces north toward the river, where floor-to-ceiling glass windows offer an unobstructed panoramic view of the entire Yuzhong Peninsula: the Chaotianmen Raffles City twin towers, Hongyadong complex, Qiansimen Bridge, and Jiangbeizui CBD arrayed before you—one of the best positions for photographing the classic Yuzhong Peninsula skyline, especially stunning at sunset and after dark. Riding from the South Station toward the North, the cabin descends from the south bank highland toward the river, with the view transitioning from a panoramic overlook to eye-level with the river surface and then looking up at the Yuzhong Peninsula towers—a perspective complementary to the ascending view from the North Station. A 5-minute walk from the station reaches Longmenhao Old Street, and 10 minutes reaches the Dongshuimen Bridge walkway—an ideal node linking the cableway experience with south bank riverside touring.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_yangtze_cableway_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '鹅岭二厂文创公园大门',
  name_en = 'Eling Factory II Main Gate',
  body = '<p>The main gate preserves the original 1930s sawtooth-roofed brick and steel-window structure of the Central Bank Printing Works, updated in 2014 with a "TESTBED 2" typographic wall and retro street lamps. It is the signature photo stop for first-time visitors.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '二厂记忆博物馆',
  name_en = 'Factory II Memory Museum',
  body = '<p>Housed in the original 8-metre-high brick hall of Building 5, the museum exhibits intaglio printing presses, numbering machines and engraved plates from the 1930s Central Bank Printing Works, plus a section on Chongqing''s wartime industrial history. Free admission.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_07';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '民国中央银行印钞厂旧址（9 号楼）',
  name_en = 'Former Central Bank Printing Works (Building 9)',
  body = '<p>Built in 1937 to print wartime currency, Building 9 is a three-storey 5,200 sqm brick building in "工" shape, designated a Chongqing Municipal Cultural Relic in 2013. Today the ground floor houses a café and design store; upper floors host artists-in-residence and photography studios.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_08';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = 'Test Design 街巷',
  name_en = 'Test Design Alley',
  body = '<p>Lined with red-brick warehouses converted into designer boutiques for fashion, homeware and jewelry, Test Design Alley is the park''s busiest retail street. A "Chongqing Forest" graffiti wall sits mid-alley.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_09';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = 'Test Joy 街巷',
  name_en = 'Test Joy Alley',
  body = '<p>A 5–7 metre-high converted warehouse alley for immersive escape rooms, live houses and themed restaurants, Test Joy is the park''s "east design, west entertainment" companion to Test Design.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_10';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '爱情天台（CITY-RADIO 电台墙）',
  name_en = 'Love Rooftop (CITY-RADIO Wall)',
  body = '<p>Filmed in the 2016 movie "I Belonged to You," the rooftop''s "CITY-RADIO" mural has become a must-photograph spot. The wall features a virtual radio dial, microphone and a working mailbox.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_13';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '云上天台',
  name_en = 'Cloud-top Rooftop',
  body = '<p>At ~380 m elevation, the wooden-decked platform offers unobstructed 360° views of the Yangtze and Jialing rivers, Yuzhong peninsula, Jiefangbei CBD, and on clear days, the Jinyun Mountain horizon.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_14';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '螺旋楼梯和涂鸦巷',
  name_en = 'Spiral Staircase & Graffiti Alley',
  body = '<p>The 4-storey black-steel spiral staircase wraps a former silo, while the 80-metre alley beyond is painted by 12 Chinese graffiti artists with themes from Chongqing''s mountains, rivers and cyberpunk cityscape.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '巨型拉链雕塑',
  name_en = 'Giant Zipper Sculpture',
  body = '<p>A 7-metre-high brick wall pierced by a 6-metre stainless-steel zipper, installed in 2017 by a CAFA sculpture team. It symbolizes "unzipping industrial heritage for creative rebirth."</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '下沉广场',
  name_en = 'Sunken Plaza',
  body = '<p>Sunken 6 m into the original raw-material yard, the 1,800 sqm plaza links Test Design (north), Test Joy (south), Test Spirit (west) and the rooftop elevators (east). A preserved steam locomotive anchors the courtyard.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '重庆书局',
  name_en = 'Chongqing Bookstore',
  body = '<p>A 1,200 sqm two-storey bookstore with 20,000+ titles, a Chongqing local-literature section, a design goods floor and a café—linked to Test Spirit Alley.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '你好童年怀旧馆',
  name_en = 'Hello Childhood Nostalgia Museum',
  body = '<p>An 800 sqm immersive nostalgia museum with thousands of 1970s–90s Chinese objects—enamel mugs, tin frogs, glass marbles, cassette games, and a recreated 1980s classroom with chalkboard desks.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_06';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = 'Test Spirit 街巷',
  name_en = 'Test Spirit Alley',
  body = '<p>Converted from original warehouses 4 and 6, Test Spirit is the park''s quietest alley—lined with tea houses, incense studios, yoga spaces and the "Shiguang" second-hand bookshop. Its plant wall and reading steps form a favourite photo spot.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_11';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = 'T²国际当代艺术中心',
  name_en = 'T² International Contemporary Art Center',
  body = '<p>Occupying the top floors of the converted office Building 1, T² runs 1,800 sqm of exhibition space and residencies. It has staged over 100 contemporary shows since 2016 and partners with Sichuan Fine Arts Institute.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_eling_2nd_factory_sa_12';
